{"title":"A Clock Measures A Path","idea_type":"model","source_basis":["Mode: Critique mode. Two adjacent records already claimed that clocks coordinate action and that clocks externalize a held stretch; this run tests a narrower physical angle before adding another teaching.","Required local comparison: observations/claude/2026-05-29-time-is-held-not-counted.md. Real disagreement: a clock does not need a humanly held past, present, and future in order to tick. That holding is needed for human interpretation, promise, and care, not for physical measurement itself.","Required local comparison: observations/codex/2026-05-29-clocks-do-not-own-time.md. Difference: that finding limits the authority of clocks; this one says what a clock positively measures, a path-dependent count of physical change along one worldline.","Primary physics: Einstein, On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies, section 1, defines event time through local clock readings and synchronization between A-time and B-time; https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/On_the_Electrodynamics_of_Moving_Bodies_(1920_edition).","Primary physics: Minkowski, Space and Time, joins space and time into world-points and introduces proper time along a world-line; https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Translation:Space_and_Time.","Closest prior argument: Howard Stein, Richard Arthur, Dennis Dieks, and Steven Savitt on local becoming, proper time, point presents, and causal diamonds, summarized in Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Being and Becoming in Modern Physics; https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/spacetime-bebecome/.","Quantum and relational pressure: Rovelli, Partial Observables, and Page and Wootters, Evolution Without Evolution, treat time through relations, correlations, and internal clocks rather than an independent flow; notes/source-cards/quantum-gravity-time-rovelli-partial-observables.md and notes/source-cards/quantum-gravity-time-page-and-wootters-evolution-without-evolution.md.","Primary contemplative comparison: Augustine, Confessions XI, says past and future are present as memory and expectation, and rejects the idea that time is simply the motion of heavenly bodies; https://www.newadvent.org/fathers/110111.htm.","Primary contemplative comparison: Dogen, Shobogenzo Uji, refuses separation between being and time and warns against treating time as merely flying away; notes/source-cards/buddhism-dogen-uji.md.","Primary contemplative comparison: Plotinus, Enneads III.7, distinguishes eternity from time and treats time as succession produced from a lower, moving life; https://sacred-texts.com/cla/plotenn/enn252.htm and https://sacred-texts.com/cla/plotenn/enn262.htm.","Practitioner-method source: Augustine's inward observation was used as the first lens, watching how memory, attention, and expectation make duration legible. Critique of method: it can mistake the human reading of time for the physical basis of time, so it was corrected by Einstein's synchronization method, Minkowski proper time, and Dogen's refusal of a spectator outside time.","Modern human-condition grounding: APA Stress in America 2024, Curran and Hill on rising perfectionism, WHO burn-out as an occupational phenomenon, and Gallup State of the Global Workplace 2024 source cards ground the wound of time pressure, comparison, overwork, and worth tied to visible progress."],"original_claim":"A clock does not measure a river of time, and it does not by itself hold past, present, and future. It measures the path of a physical system through change: a count of repeatable transitions along one worldline, later compared with other records. The felt now is not an illusion inside a finished block. It is the local point where records have reached this body, action is still possible, and responsibility can be taken from here. The crux is whether this path-bound now is real enough for conduct without becoming a private metaphysics. There is no single cosmic now in which every life is early, late, ahead, or behind. There are many local nows that can coordinate with each other, and modern suffering begins when another path's clock is borrowed as a verdict on one's own life.","why_it_might_be_new":"The closest prior argument is local becoming in relativity: Stein, Arthur, Dieks, and Savitt already treat proper time, light cones, and causal diamonds as ways to avoid a single global present. The distinct move is not to claim a new physics of time. It is to connect proper-time locality, Dogen's being-time, Augustine's inward measurement, and modern comparison stress into one doctrine candidate: clocks coordinate paths, but they should not make one path the judge of all paths. Prior art asks whether becoming can survive relativity; this asks how a person should live when physics removes the fantasy of one shared cosmic schedule.","critique":"The strongest objection is that the idea may be local becoming with spiritual and therapeutic clothing. Proper time already says that a clock measures along a worldline, and philosophy of physics has already explored local presents. Dogen may also reject the phrase 'my path' because it risks separating a self from being-time, while Augustine may pull the model too far inward. A social anomaly would weaken it further: caregivers, workers, students, and teams often live under shared deadlines that are not merely borrowed comparison clocks. If path language makes people less punctual, less honest about obligations, or more accepting of structural overload, the teaching should be revised or retired.","epistemic_labels":["textual","interpretive","phenomenological","empirical-adjacent","analogical","speculative"],"scores":{"novelty":0.5,"generativity":0.84,"cross_tradition_support":0.66,"logical_coherence":0.79,"explanatory_compression":0.78,"empirical_adjacency":0.7,"practice_testability":0.74,"counterargument_quality":0.88,"source_reliability":0.84,"publishability":0.68},"next_research_directions":["If this model is right, then people taught to distinguish owed coordination times from borrowed comparison times should show less 'I am late in life' language without becoming less punctual. If avoidance rises or obligations are missed, the model is weakened.","If this model is right, then a relativity lesson that begins with proper time along worldlines should produce fewer claims that the felt present is simply an illusion than a lesson that begins with the block universe. If both lessons produce the same illusion claim, the path framing adds little.","Close-read Dogen Uji against Stein, Dieks, and Arthur. If Dogen's non-separation makes path language reify a self moving through time, revise the teaching toward 'answer from this situation' rather than 'stay with your path.'","Protocol improvement: future time runs should pair every inward observation of duration with a physical clock account before letting lived time carry metaphysical weight."],"teaching_candidate":{"title":"Stay With Your Own Path","teaching_line":"Use another person's clock for meeting them, not for measuring your worth.","doctrine_claim":"A life is answerable from the path it actually travels. Clocks coordinate paths; they do not create one court in which every life is late.","body":"A clock can tell you when to arrive. It cannot tell you that someone else's season is your failure.\n\nYou have one body, one history, and one set of duties that can be reached from here. Compare calendars when you must coordinate with others. Do not compare lives as if all paths share one starting line and one finish.\n\nWhen time tightens, ask what has actually reached you, who is truly waiting on you, and what can be answered now.","target_human_problem":"Achievement-contingent self-worth, digital comparison, deadline anxiety, and burnout fed by feeling behind other people's lives.","target_cohort":"Responsible adults who meet many obligations but feel late because peer milestones, public timelines, career clocks, or family expectations are constantly visible.","pressure_survived":"Survived close reading of Einstein's clock synchronization, Minkowski proper time, Augustine's inward measurement, Dogen's no-separation, Plotinus on eternity and succession, and prior-art pressure from local becoming in relativity.","falsifying_pressure":"Weakens if the teaching reduces shame mainly by encouraging avoidance, lateness, or withdrawal from real duties. Also weakens if a fuller prior-art audit shows that local becoming literature already makes this same ethical and practice claim.","status":"under_dialogue","tags":["time","proper-time","comparison","burnout","achievement-pressure","being-time","method-authority"]},"practice_candidate":{"title":"Whose Clock Is This?","practice_line":"When time becomes a verdict, name the actual path it belongs to.","purpose":"To test whether separating coordination from comparison reduces time shame while preserving responsibility.","target_human_problem":"Time anxiety, digital comparison, burnout, and self-worth tied to visible progress or deadlines.","target_cohort":"Students, knowledge workers, caregivers, founders, artists, and professionals who are generally functioning but feel behind because other people's timelines are visible.","non_fit":"Not for emergencies, acute crisis, addiction withdrawal, severe depression, mania, psychosis, or people currently avoiding concrete obligations. Not a substitute for planning, rest, therapy, medical care, or workplace boundary changes.","duration":"4 minutes","frequency":"Once daily for ten days, plus once after a comparison spike.","minimum_attempt":"Five attempts before judging fit.","steps":["Write the clock or timeline that is judging you: deadline, age, peer milestone, feed, calendar, or family expectation.","Ask: is this an owed coordination time, or a borrowed comparison time?","If it is owed, name who or what is affected and choose one concrete action or honest message.","If it is borrowed, name one path difference: body, duty, grief, resource, training, season, or responsibility.","Choose one action from your actual path for the next hour.","Stop after choosing. Do not turn the practice into a life review."],"notice":["Whether the body loosens or tightens after naming the clock.","Whether responsibility becomes clearer or avoidance becomes easier.","Whether shame about being behind decreases without losing care for people waiting on you.","Whether the practice becomes another way to monitor yourself."],"caution":"Stop if the practice becomes an excuse for lateness, increases rumination, feeds self-attack, or hides a real obligation. If time pressure comes from exploitation or unsafe conditions, seek practical and human support rather than spiritualizing the pressure.","weakens_if":"Weakens if it reduces shame only by avoiding duties, increases missed commitments, adds no difference beyond ordinary planning, or makes comparison thoughts more frequent after ten days.","risk_level":"low","status":"seed","tags":["time","comparison","deadline-anxiety","burnout","practice-seed","low-risk"]},"tests":[{"title":"Local Becoming Prior Art Audit","test_type":"prior-art","target_type":"idea","prediction":"If the idea is distinct, Stein, Arthur, Dieks, Savitt, Dorato, Wittman, and Rovelli should discuss proper-time locality and relativistic presents without deriving the same targeted teaching about borrowed comparison clocks and self-worth. If that ethical and practice claim is already present, novelty should fall below 0.35.","result":"pending","impact":"pending","next_action":"Close-read the local becoming literature, especially Arthur 2019, Dieks 1988 and 2006, Savitt 2009 and 2020, Dorato and Wittman 2015, and Rovelli 2019 on finite bubble presents.","status":"proposed"},{"title":"Borrowed Clock Diary","test_type":"practice-report","target_type":"practice","prediction":"If this model is right, ten days of Whose Clock Is This? should reduce comparison-driven statements like 'I am behind in life' while preserving or improving completion of owed timed tasks. If distress falls mainly through avoidance or lateness, the model is weakened.","result":"pending","impact":"pending","next_action":"Run a small diary study with functioning adults under deadline and comparison pressure. Track comparison shame, completed obligations, honest messages sent, and missed commitments.","status":"proposed"},{"title":"Proper-Time Teaching Test","test_type":"cross-domain","target_type":"idea","prediction":"If this model is right, learners who receive a proper-time and worldline-first explanation of relativity should be less likely to conclude that the lived present is fake than learners who receive a block-universe-first explanation. If both groups conclude this at similar rates, the teaching value is weakened.","result":"pending","impact":"pending","next_action":"Draft two matched short lessons and compare learner takeaways about clocks, worldlines, the block universe, and lived responsibility.","status":"proposed"},{"title":"Dogen No-Separation Pressure","test_type":"falsification-attempt","target_type":"teaching","prediction":"If Uji makes 'my path' a reifying separation between self and time, the teaching should be revised away from path ownership. If 'path' can be held as a dependent local standpoint for action, the teaching survives with caution.","result":"pending","impact":"pending","next_action":"Close-read Uji with a Soto Zen practitioner or scholar, then test whether the teaching sounds like no-separation in modern language or like individualist self-protection.","status":"proposed"},{"title":"Responsibility Leakage Check","test_type":"safety","target_type":"practice","prediction":"If the practice is safe for the target cohort, users should report clearer owed actions, not weaker duties. If users use it to dismiss other people's needs or soften preventable delay, the practice should be weakened or retired.","result":"pending","impact":"pending","next_action":"Add a post-practice question: 'What real person or duty might I be ignoring?' Review reports before any public practice promotion.","status":"proposed"}]}
